{{Infobox film | name = It Girls | image = | alt = | caption = | film name = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)--> | director = [[Robin Melanie Leacock]] | producer = <!-- or: |producers = --> | writer = <!-- or: |writers = --> | screenplay = | story = | based on = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} --> | starring = | narrator = <!-- or: |narrators = --> | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = <!-- or: |production companies = --> | distributor = <!-- or: |distributors = --> | released = {{film date|2002|04}} | runtime = | country = United States | language = | budget = | gross = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. "£11.6 million" not "£11,586,221")--> }} '''''It Girls''''' is a feature documentary film directed by [[Robin Melanie Leacock]] that aired on the [[WE tv|Women's Entertainment]] channel on April 2 and 7 2002. It features wealthy socialites including [[Casey Johnson]],<ref>{{cite journal |title=Casey at Bat |author=Kimberly Cutter |date=August 2003 |journal=[[W Magazine]]}} reprinted at http://www.wmagazine.com/w/blogs/editorsblog/2010/01/07/vintage-casey-johnson-in-w-une.htm</ref> Elisabeth Kieselstein-Cord and [[Nicky Hilton]], as well as appearances by [[Diane Von Furstenberg]], Marisa Berenson and other women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0204/02/ltm.19.html |title='It Girls' To Look at Interesting Women |last1=Zahn |first1=Paula |last2=Cooper |first2=Anderson |date=2 April 2002 |work=American Morning |publisher=CNN.COM |accessdate=8 January 2010 |postscript= &nbsp;(Transcript of broadcast interview with the director and two of the performers in the documentary)}}</ref> It was filmed in [[Manhattan]] during [[Fashion Week]]. The film's premise is that anyone can be an [[it girl]]. In the documentary, von Furstenberg says "It's really about being a forever girl!"{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}
==Critical response== Roger Friedman, writing for Fox News, said that this was a "numbingly mesmerizing documentary" in which "You have rarely seen such a collection of vacuous and tiresome people". He complains that "the 'It Girls' of 2002... are an inarticulate and alarming lot of long legged blondes without a thought in their heads".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,49223,00.html |title= Oprah: No Shocks or Klan Members |first=Roger |last=Friedman |date=1 April 2002 |publisher=Fox News |accessdate=8 January 2010}}</ref>
Mary Robbins, in the ''[[New York Times]]'', wrote that the film suffered from poor timing, because the bad economic conditions at the time had "made expensive parties, and girls who were famous for nothing, less and less appealing."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/07/style/where-have-all-the-it-girls-gone.html?pagewanted=1 |title=Where Have All The It Girls Gone? |first=Mary |last=Robbins |date=7 April 2002 |work=New York Times (page 99 of the New York edition) |publisher=New York Times Company |accessdate=8 January 2010}} </ref> <!--''[[Women's Wear Daily]]'' reported mixed reactions from a variety of New York city residents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-25270716_ITM |title=WHAT IS 'IT,' ANYWAY?(Robin Leacock's It Girls) |date=2 April 2002 |publisher=[[Women's Wear Daily]] |accessdate=8 January 2010}} </ref>-->
A reviewer for the ''Baltimore Sun'' wrote: "As if high school social castes weren't traumatic enough. This "documentary" allegedly attempts to explore the new It Girl, but really reminds us that the hierarchy we like to think we left behind in high school is alive and kicking in the adult world." and "Even with its occasional snarky snippets, the show can be hard to endure for those of us among the proletariat. But after a while, the documentary begins to resemble a drama, and the Hilton girls and their beautiful friends become mere characters in a nouveau Restoration comedy -- [[School for Scandal]] meets Page Six."<ref>{{cite news |title=In a high-society game of glamour -- they're It |author=Cheryl Lu-Lien Tan |newspaper=The Baltimore Sun |date=7 April 2002 |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2002-04-07/entertainment/0204070401_1_paris-hilton-girls-johnson |accessdate=9 January 2010}}</ref>
